t period to the present day. Through studies of various cultural manifestations including festivals, human tower-building, gastronomy, and bull-runs, chapters explore how civil mobilisation, women's increasing participation in the public sphere, and issues of gentrification and heritagisation have intertwined with identity politics and nationalist trends. An important consideration is how a popular culture centred on sociability responded to the lockdowns and restrictions of the COVID-19 pandemic. More generally, the book reflects on the politicisation of culture and its role in nation-building, problematising such concepts as 'inclusion', 'integration', 'authenticity', 'belonging', and 'identity'.Contributors: Lluís Bellas, Camila del Mármol, Manuel Delgado, Mireia Guil, Venetia Johannes, Sarai Martín López, Romina Martínez Algueró, Dorothy Noyes, Xavier Roigé, Alessandro Testa, Mariann Vaczi  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEthnicityzSpainzCatalonia. 0aPopular culturezSpainzCatalonia. 4aHispanic Studies. 4aPolitics & Economics. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh  aCatalan.  aCatalanness.  aCathar.  acarnival.  acorrebous.  acuisine.  adigitalisation.  afolklore.  agastronomy.  anacionalisme.  anationalism.  apactisme.  apoliticization.  arituality.  atradition.1 aAlgueró, Romina Martínez, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBellas, Lluís, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDelgado, Manuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuil, Mireia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohannes, Venetia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLópez, Sarai Martín, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voc